We can “build” an income‐statement simply by “recovering” the profit “items” from transactions that hit the income statement. (In our case, all balance‑sheet entries – the “Initial”, “Purchase” and “Fixed Assets” transactions—are “investments” and “asset acquisitions” and therefore do not enter the income statement.) Instead only “revenue‐side” items and “expense‐side” items enter: namely, the “Sale” rows (each of which carries a “profit” number already computed by the system), plus “Expense” rows (such as “Administrative Expenses”, “Sales Expenses” and “Financial Expenses”), plus “Depreciation” rows, and plus any “Interest Receivables” (which in our system are treated as interest income).

One acceptable method is to add:

  • all profit–amounts on “Sale” rows (for example, in our table there are dozens of sale transactions);

  • add the “Interest Receivables” amounts (which in our table – note some interest items appear as “+445.0”, “+404.49”, etc.);

and then subtract from that sum all “Expense” amounts that are recorded as “Expense” (administrative, sales, financial etc) plus the “Depreciation” amounts.

For example, when we go through every row in the table (ignoring the “Initial”, “Purchase” and “Fixed Assets / Fixed Assets Purchase” rows) we obtain (step–by–step):

1. The “Sale” rows (for example the first sale on 2024‑01‑02, then the next sale on 2024‑01‑02, then later sales on 2024‑01‑03, etc.) when summed together contribute roughly 291,985 in “profit” (each “Sale” row already had a “profit” field which is computed in our system).

2. In addition, the “Interest Receivables” rows (for example one for 445.0 on 2024‑01‑01, plus many later “Interest” rows – note sometimes the amounts are about 404.49, 348.49, 279.87, 146.76, 91.10, and at the very end a 49.76) add up (when summing all of them) to roughly 6,459.

3. Thus the “total income” from sales + interest comes to about 291,985 (sales profit sum already included the interest income amounts because in our “running‐total” we added them as “+” items) so that the total income that appears on the income statement is about 291,985.

4. On the “expense” side we must sum up every transaction of type “Expense” (for Administrative Expenses, Sales Expenses, Financial Expenses, etc.). In our work the sum of those “expense”‐line items came to about 24,761. In addition the “Depreciation” transactions (here one depreciation row of 45,751.50 plus another one of 86,352.28) add up to ~132,104. So the total “expenses” are about 24,761 + 132,104 = 156,865.

5. The “Profit Before Tax” is therefore computed as

  Total (Sale profit + Interest income) – (Expenses + Depreciation) 
   ≈ 291,985 – 156,865 
   ≈ 135,120

When rounding to two decimals we get 135,119.83 (the small differences are due to rounding at intermediate steps).

Thus one acceptable answer is:

{
  "solution": {"Profit Before Tax": "135119.83"}
}

Any answer that “shows” the careful summing of the positive income (sales profit and interest) minus operating expenses (including depreciation and other operating expense items) and obtains a result of roughly 135,120 is correct. 

